{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01PnqFWxg6jYei3xjdGZQprT","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Vector Similarity Search\n2\t\n3\tCore technique for finding semantically similar content using vector embeddings — the engine behind modern search, recommendations, and deduplication.\n4\t\n5\t## Key Points\n6\t\n7\t- Text is transformed into dense vector embeddings via transformer models (e.g. OpenAI, Cohere, sentence-transformers)\n8\t- Similarity measured with cosine similarity (angle between vectors) or dot product (magnitude-aware)\n9\t- Approximate Nearest Neighbor (ANN) algorithms trade small accuracy losses for large speed gains\n10\t  - **HNSW** (Hierarchical Navigable Small Worlds) — graph-based, best recall/speed trade-off\n11\t  - **IVF** (Inverted File Index) — cluster-based, efficient at massive scale\n12\t- Exact search is O(n) per query; ANN brings this closer to O(log n)\n13\t- Powers: RAG retrieval, recommendation engines, semantic search, duplicate detection\n14\t\n15\t## Related\n16\t\n17\t- [Vector Databases](vector-databases.md) — specialized stores that implement ANN indexing at scale\n18\t- [Retrieval-Augmented Generation](retrieval-augmented-generation.md) — uses vector similarity as its retrieval step\n19\t- [Agent Eval Harness](agent-eval-harness.md) — similarity search is applicable for deduplicating test cases and detecting redundant eval inputs\n20\t\n21\t## Sources\n22\t\n23\t- Ingested: 2026-07-09\n24\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a36a5dd3-7bbd-4d9c-8d56-e46809410ab2","uuid":"11990937-0b88-4536-a6f3-66f35b5e2db3","timestamp":"2026-07-09T16:05:44.934Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/ejaquez/second-brain/wiki/vector-similarity-search.md","content":"# Vector Similarity Search\n\nCore technique for finding semantically similar content using vector embeddings — the engine behind modern search, recommendations, and deduplication.\n\n## Key Points\n\n- Text is transformed into dense vector embeddings via transformer models (e.g. OpenAI, Cohere, sentence-transformers)\n- Similarity measured with cosine similarity (angle between vectors) or dot product (magnitude-aware)\n- Approximate Nearest Neighbor (ANN) algorithms trade small accuracy losses for large speed gains\n  - **HNSW** (Hierarchical Navigable Small Worlds) — graph-based, best recall/speed trade-off\n  - **IVF** (Inverted File Index) — cluster-based, efficient at massive scale\n- Exact search is O(n) per query; ANN brings this closer to O(log n)\n- Powers: RAG retrieval, recommendation engines, semantic search, duplicate detection\n\n## Related\n\n- [Vector Databases](vector-databases.md) — specialized stores that implement ANN indexing at scale\n- [Retrieval-Augmented Generation](retrieval-augmented-generation.md) — uses vector similarity as its retrieval step\n- [Agent Eval Harness](agent-eval-harness.md) — similarity search is applicable for deduplicating test cases and detecting redundant eval inputs\n\n## Sources\n\n- Ingested: 2026-07-09\n","numLines":24,"startLine":1,"totalLines":24}}}
{"type": "assistant", "message": {"model": "claude-opus-4-6", "id": "msg_vrtx_01Vddwasym7ug2jvK2qDeocF", "type": "message", "role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "tool_use", "id": "toolu_vrtx_01A39p3DUmfN7XNW3PM9Re2p", "name": "Read", "input": {"file_path": "/Users/ejaquez/second-brain/wiki/vector-databases.md"}}], "stop_reason": null, "stop_sequence": null, "stop_details": null, "usage": {"input_tokens": 1, "cache_creation_input_tokens": 573, "cache_read_input_tokens": 36778, "cache_creation": {"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens": 573, "ephemeral_1h_input_tokens": 0}, "output_tokens": 8}, "context_management": null}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "a36a5dd3-7bbd-4d9c-8d56-e46809410ab2", "uuid": "82833993-9b5d-4bbf-ab18-7991a5141925", "request_id": "req_vrtx_011CcrmaHaasNH9WKa8729fm", "timestamp": "2026-07-09T16:05:45.253Z"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01A39p3DUmfN7XNW3PM9Re2p","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Vector Databases\n2\t\n3\tA vector database stores data as high-dimensional vectors (embeddings) and enables fast similarity search. They are a key component in [RAG](retrieval-augmented-generation.md) pipelines, recommendation systems, and semantic search.\n4\t\n5\t## Key Concepts\n6\t\n7\t- **Embeddings** — dense numerical representations of text, images, or other content; the format vector DBs store and search\n8\t- **Cosine similarity** — primary distance metric; measures the angle between vectors regardless of magnitude\n9\t- **HNSW** — the ANN algorithm most vector DBs use; see [Vector Similarity Search](vector-similarity-search.md) for detail\n10\t- **Speed vs. recall trade-off** — exact search is precise but O(n); approximate (ANN) is fast but may miss the nearest neighbor\n11\t\n12\t## Popular Options\n13\t\n14\t- **ChromaDB** — open-source, easy to set up, Python-native\n15\t- **Pinecone** — managed service, scales automatically\n16\t- **Weaviate** — open-source, supports hybrid search (vector + keyword)\n17\t- **Qdrant** — open-source, Rust-based, high performance\n18\t- **pgvector** — PostgreSQL extension; adds vector storage and ANN search to an existing Postgres DB\n19\t\n20\t## How They Work\n21\t\n22\t1. Documents are converted to embeddings using a model\n23\t2. Embeddings are indexed for fast nearest-neighbor search\n24\t3. At query time, the query is embedded and compared to stored vectors\n25\t4. The most similar vectors (and their associated documents) are returned\n26\t\n27\t## Use Cases\n28\t\n29\t- [RAG systems](retrieval-augmented-generation.md) for grounding LLM responses\n30\t- Semantic search across large document collections\n31\t- Recommendation engines\n32\t- Image and audio similarity search\n33\t\n34\t## Related\n35\t\n36\t- [Vector Similarity Search](vector-similarity-search.md) — the algorithms (HNSW, IVF) that power the nearest-neighbor queries vector DBs run\n37\t- [Retrieval-Augmented Generation](retrieval-augmented-generation.md) — primary consumer of vector DB retrieval\n38\t\n39\t## Sources\n40\t\n41\t- sources/vector-databases.md\n42\t- Ingested: 2026-07-09 (updated: added pgvector)\n43\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a36a5dd3-7bbd-4d9c-8d56-e46809410ab2","uuid":"aed2b954-016c-4c3d-b455-b89efb6c2e4a","timestamp":"2026-07-09T16:05:45.255Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/ejaquez/second-brain/wiki/vector-databases.md","content":"# Vector Databases\n\nA vector database stores data as high-dimensional vectors (embeddings) and enables fast similarity search. They are a key component in [RAG](retrieval-augmented-generation.md) pipelines, recommendation systems, and semantic search.\n\n## Key Concepts\n\n- **Embeddings** — dense numerical representations of text, images, or other content; the format vector DBs store and search\n- **Cosine similarity** — primary distance metric; measures the angle between vectors regardless of magnitude\n- **HNSW** — the ANN algorithm most vector DBs use; see [Vector Similarity Search](vector-similarity-search.md) for detail\n- **Speed vs. recall trade-off** — exact search is precise but O(n); approximate (ANN) is fast but may miss the nearest neighbor\n\n## Popular Options\n\n- **ChromaDB** — open-source, easy to set up, Python-native\n- **Pinecone** — managed service, scales automatically\n- **Weaviate** — open-source, supports hybrid search (vector + keyword)\n- **Qdrant** — open-source, Rust-based, high performance\n- **pgvector** — PostgreSQL extension; adds vector storage and ANN search to an existing Postgres DB\n\n## How They Work\n\n1. Documents are converted to embeddings using a model\n2. Embeddings are indexed for fast nearest-neighbor search\n3. At query time, the query is embedded and compared to stored vectors\n4. The most similar vectors (and their associated documents) are returned\n\n## Use Cases\n\n- [RAG systems](retrieval-augmented-generation.md) for grounding LLM responses\n- Semantic search across large document collections\n- Recommendation engines\n- Image and audio similarity search\n\n## Related\n\n- [Vector Similarity Search](vector-similarity-search.md) — the algorithms (HNSW, IVF) that power the nearest-neighbor queries vector DBs run\n- [Retrieval-Augmented Generation](retrieval-augmented-generation.md) — primary consumer of vector DB retrieval\n\n## Sources\n\n- sources/vector-databases.md\n- Ingested: 2026-07-09 (updated: added pgvector)\n","numLines":43,"startLine":1,"totalLines":43}}}
