{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_014akVa6ipiQ6enks6cznuc8","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Retrieval-Augmented Generation\n2\t\n3\tRetrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) is a technique that enhances LLM responses by retrieving relevant documents from an external knowledge base before generating an answer. Instead of relying solely on the model's training data, RAG grounds responses in real, up-to-date documents.\n4\t\n5\t## How It Works\n6\t\n7\t1. A user asks a question\n8\t2. The system searches a document store (e.g. a [vector database](vector-databases.md), keyword index) for relevant chunks\n9\t3. Those chunks are injected into the LLM prompt as context\n10\t4. The LLM generates an answer grounded in the retrieved documents\n11\t\n12\t## Benefits\n13\t\n14\t- **Reduces hallucination** — answers are grounded in real documents\n15\t- **Updatable without retraining** — swap or add documents anytime\n16\t- **Works with proprietary data** — keeps domain-specific knowledge accessible\n17\t\n18\t## Limitations\n19\t\n20\t- Quality depends heavily on the retrieval step — bad retrieval means bad answers\n21\t- Large documents may require chunking strategies to fit context windows\n22\t- Embedding models add latency and cost to the pipeline\n23\t\n24\t## Common Tools\n25\t\n26\t- **Orchestration:** LangChain, LlamaIndex\n27\t- **Vector storage:** ChromaDB, Pinecone, Weaviate (see [Vector Databases](vector-databases.md))\n28\t- **Embeddings:** OpenAI, Cohere, or open-source models\n29\t\n30\t## Related\n31\t\n32\t- [Vector Similarity Search](vector-similarity-search.md) — the mechanism behind the retrieval step\n33\t- [Vector Databases](vector-databases.md) — the storage layer that indexes embeddings for fast retrieval\n34\t\n35\t## Sources\n36\t\n37\t- sources/what-is-rag.md\n38\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a36a5dd3-7bbd-4d9c-8d56-e46809410ab2","uuid":"cc25ad96-3ddd-47a0-b64f-d0dad90d97d1","timestamp":"2026-07-09T16:05:45.494Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/ejaquez/second-brain/wiki/retrieval-augmented-generation.md","content":"# Retrieval-Augmented Generation\n\nRetrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) is a technique that enhances LLM responses by retrieving relevant documents from an external knowledge base before generating an answer. Instead of relying solely on the model's training data, RAG grounds responses in real, up-to-date documents.\n\n## How It Works\n\n1. A user asks a question\n2. The system searches a document store (e.g. a [vector database](vector-databases.md), keyword index) for relevant chunks\n3. Those chunks are injected into the LLM prompt as context\n4. The LLM generates an answer grounded in the retrieved documents\n\n## Benefits\n\n- **Reduces hallucination** — answers are grounded in real documents\n- **Updatable without retraining** — swap or add documents anytime\n- **Works with proprietary data** — keeps domain-specific knowledge accessible\n\n## Limitations\n\n- Quality depends heavily on the retrieval step — bad retrieval means bad answers\n- Large documents may require chunking strategies to fit context windows\n- Embedding models add latency and cost to the pipeline\n\n## Common Tools\n\n- **Orchestration:** LangChain, LlamaIndex\n- **Vector storage:** ChromaDB, Pinecone, Weaviate (see [Vector Databases](vector-databases.md))\n- **Embeddings:** OpenAI, Cohere, or open-source models\n\n## Related\n\n- [Vector Similarity Search](vector-similarity-search.md) — the mechanism behind the retrieval step\n- [Vector Databases](vector-databases.md) — the storage layer that indexes embeddings for fast retrieval\n\n## Sources\n\n- sources/what-is-rag.md\n","numLines":38,"startLine":1,"totalLines":38}}}
